00:39.200 --> 00:43.080
<i>Let us praise famous men...</i>

00:44.000 --> 00:46.080
<i>and our fathers that begat us.</i>

00:48.040 --> 00:50.080
<i>All these men...</i>

00:50.160 --> 00:52.400
<i>were honoured in their generations...</i>

00:52.480 --> 00:56.400
<i>and were a glory in their days.</i>

00:56.480 --> 01:00.440
We are here today to give thanks...

01:00.560 --> 01:03.880
for the life of Harold Abrahams.

01:05.519 --> 01:08.480
To honour the legend.

01:09.560 --> 01:12.120
Now there are just two of us...

01:12.200 --> 01:14.720
young Aubrey Montague...

01:14.800 --> 01:17.040
and myself...

01:17.120 --> 01:19.640
who can close our eyes...

01:19.720 --> 01:23.800
and remember those few young men...

01:23.880 --> 01:26.400
with hope in our hearts...

01:26.480 --> 01:30.080
<i>and wings on our heels.</i>

04:07.220 --> 04:10.340
<i>Carlton Hotel, Broadstairs, Kent.</i>

04:10.420 --> 04:12.500
<i>28th June, 1924.</i>

04:12.700 --> 04:17.300
<i>Dear Mum. I'm most awfully sorry about</i>
<i>your cold and the general dreariness.</i>

04:17.380 --> 04:19.940
<i>We're also having</i>
<i>quite bad weather here, too.</i>

04:20.060 --> 04:23.540
<i>Thanks for your letters.</i>
<i>I'm sorry you and Pa are disappointed...</i>

04:23.620 --> 04:27.460
<i>I should be letting the Olympic Games</i>
<i>interfere with my shorthand.</i>

04:27.540 --> 04:31.940
<i>But if you were my age, with a chance</i>
<i>to win the World Championship in Paris...</i>

04:32.020 --> 04:34.380
<i>you would be just as big a fool as I am.</i>

04:34.460 --> 04:39.020
<i>By the way, it's awfully kind of Pa</i>
<i>to finance me here, in spite of my idiocy.</i>

04:39.100 --> 04:43.260
<i>It's marvellous for esprit de corps.</i>
<i>Most of the chaps have managed to get down.</i>

04:43.340 --> 04:46.340
- Cricket, Montague, in the ballroom.
- Now!

04:47.860 --> 04:49.780
No ball!

04:49.860 --> 04:51.940
Come on, Aubrey, the old leg break.

05:02.900 --> 05:05.980
- Howzat!
- Not out.

05:06.060 --> 05:08.580
What? You could hear it
in bloody Bournemouth!

05:08.660 --> 05:11.340
- Come on, Liddell, my innings.
- I didn't touch it.

05:11.420 --> 05:15.140
- You heard the crack of my wrist.
- I saw the bloody thing bend!
- Andy!

05:15.220 --> 05:17.220
No tickle for me.

05:17.300 --> 05:20.380
He's out, I tell you.
You're all deaf and bloody blind.

05:20.460 --> 05:23.180
Aubrey, I ask you, for God's sake!

05:27.220 --> 05:29.300
It's not fair!

05:34.820 --> 05:36.700
All right.

05:40.020 --> 05:42.540
<i>Harold's here. As intense as ever.</i>

05:42.620 --> 05:45.700
<i>Just as he was</i>
<i>on our very first day at Cambridge.</i>

05:45.780 --> 05:47.860
<i>I remember we shared a taxi together.</i>

06:14.980 --> 06:17.060
I'll take these.

06:20.900 --> 06:23.060
- See you inside, Aubrey.
- Right.

06:24.980 --> 06:27.220
Thank you.

06:31.700 --> 06:33.780
- Name, please.
- We're new.

06:33.860 --> 06:36.060
I can see that, laddie. What's your name?

06:36.140 --> 06:38.220
Abrahams. HM.

06:38.860 --> 06:42.540
- Top of the list. Repton. That the one?
- That's it. Left a year ago.

06:42.620 --> 06:46.260
- Been doing your bit, 'ave you? France?
- No. Joined too late.

06:46.340 --> 06:47.980
Bad luck, lad.

06:48.100 --> 06:50.660
Many a dead man
would have liked a share of it.

06:50.740 --> 06:52.820
You're right there, son.

06:53.700 --> 06:56.060
Welcome to Caius.

06:56.980 --> 07:00.620
- Sign here.
- Thank you.

07:00.700 --> 07:04.780
It's across the courtyard,
top right-hand corner, up the stairs.

07:04.860 --> 07:06.300
Thanks.

07:06.380 --> 07:08.020
By the way, what are your names?

07:08.100 --> 07:11.540
Rogers, head porter,
and this is Mr Ratcliffe, my assistant.

07:11.660 --> 07:13.740
Well, Mr Rogers, Ratcliffe...

07:13.820 --> 07:17.180
I ceased to be a "laddie" when
I took up the King's commission.

07:17.260 --> 07:20.580
- Is that clear?
- Yes... Mr Abrahams.

07:20.660 --> 07:22.660
- Quite clear.
- Thank you.

07:22.740 --> 07:25.220
I'd be obliged if you'd remember it.

07:25.340 --> 07:27.420
- See you later.
- Fine.

07:29.100 --> 07:31.820
What's your friend studying, then, son?

07:31.900 --> 07:33.980
Barrack-room law?

07:34.540 --> 07:36.620
I've no idea.

07:36.700 --> 07:38.420
One thing's certain.

07:38.500 --> 07:43.260
A name like Abrahams, he won't be
in the chapel choir, now, will he?

07:43.340 --> 07:45.540
- Name?
- Montague.

07:45.620 --> 07:47.700
- What?
- Montague.

08:36.820 --> 08:38.980
I take the war list...

08:39.059 --> 08:41.140
and I run down it.

08:42.580 --> 08:45.220
Name after name which I cannot read...

08:45.300 --> 08:48.700
and which we, who are older than you...

08:48.780 --> 08:51.460
cannot hear, without emotion.

08:53.020 --> 08:55.980
Names which will be only names to you...

08:56.060 --> 08:58.140
the new college.

08:58.220 --> 09:03.100
But which to us summon up face after face...

09:04.500 --> 09:08.460
full of honesty and goodness...

09:08.540 --> 09:10.420
zeal and vigour...

09:10.500 --> 09:13.300
and intellectual promise.

09:14.860 --> 09:17.100
The flower of a generation.

09:17.180 --> 09:19.220
The glory of England...

09:19.300 --> 09:21.380
and they died for England...

09:21.460 --> 09:23.780
and all that England stands for.

09:24.940 --> 09:29.260
And now by tragic necessity,
their dreams have become yours.

09:30.060 --> 09:33.260
Let me exhort you. Examine yourselves.

09:33.340 --> 09:35.420
Let each of you discover...

09:35.500 --> 09:38.700
where your true chance of greatness lies.

09:39.420 --> 09:41.500
For their sakes...

09:41.620 --> 09:46.060
for the sake of your college
and your country, seize this chance.

09:46.140 --> 09:48.220
Rejoice in it...

09:48.300 --> 09:52.780
and let no power or persuasion
deter you in your task.

09:56.020 --> 09:58.980
<i>Thursday, October 10th, 1919.</i>

09:59.060 --> 10:01.540
<i>My first day at Cambridge was rounded off...</i>

10:01.620 --> 10:04.460
<i>by the freshmen's dinner,</i>
<i>a sumptuous affair.</i>

10:04.540 --> 10:06.780
<i>The master gave us a moving speech...</i>

10:06.860 --> 10:10.540
<i>and I'm now eagerly awaiting</i>
<i>the start of term proper.</i>

10:10.900 --> 10:13.660
Rugby club, golfing society, tennis...

10:13.740 --> 10:16.740
squash club, flora and fauna, philately.

10:16.820 --> 10:18.940
Is that all? You're an idle man!

10:19.020 --> 10:22.940
- I've got to work some time.
- Try bird-watching. You can take a book.

10:23.020 --> 10:25.100
How can I watch if I'm reading a book?

10:25.180 --> 10:28.060
Follow in the footsteps of WG.
Any Yorkshiremen here?

10:28.140 --> 10:30.140
I can't bat for toffee.

10:32.100 --> 10:33.980
♪ Upon the battle scene

10:34.060 --> 10:35.780
♪ They fight the foe together

10:35.860 --> 10:37.740
♪ There every mother's son

10:37.820 --> 10:40.020
♪ Prepared to fight or fall is

10:40.100 --> 10:43.660
♪ The enemy of one the enemy of all is

10:44.140 --> 10:48.020
♪ The enemy of one the enemy of all is

10:48.900 --> 10:51.140
- Abrahams, HM.
- Can you manage a tenor?

10:51.260 --> 10:54.620
- We're desperately short of tenors.
- Only under torture.

10:54.700 --> 10:57.620
- Aubrey. Sing, do you?
- School choir, that's all.

10:57.700 --> 10:59.180
You, Stallard?

10:59.260 --> 11:01.700
They kicked me out of <i>Ring-a-ring o'Roses.</i>

11:01.780 --> 11:04.060
Sorry about that. We can't all be gifted.

11:04.140 --> 11:06.460
♪ If everybody's somebody

11:06.540 --> 11:08.780
♪ Then no one's anybody

11:08.900 --> 11:11.340
- Put my friend here down as well.
- Steady on.

11:11.420 --> 11:14.260
Splendid! Rehearsals start on Monday.
<i>Iolanthe.</i>

11:14.340 --> 11:18.580
- I was a boy alto.
- Perfect! You can be Queen of the Fairies.

11:18.700 --> 11:21.100
Where were you
when your country needed you?

11:21.180 --> 11:25.660
We have a duty, a solemn duty, to those
millions of lives needlessly slaughtered!

11:25.740 --> 11:28.580
♪ When the boys are far away

11:28.660 --> 11:33.300
♪ They dream of home

11:34.500 --> 11:36.580
Well, glad to have you, Stallard.

11:36.660 --> 11:39.140
Good middle-distance men
don't grow on trees.

11:39.260 --> 11:41.340
I can't vouch for those times.

11:42.700 --> 11:45.740
Taken with the school alarm clock,
most of them.

11:45.820 --> 11:49.140
Give or take a second,
they're good enough for me.

11:49.940 --> 11:53.300
Have you come across a fellow
called Abrahams? HM Abrahams?

11:53.380 --> 11:55.460
He's challenged for the college dash.

11:55.580 --> 11:57.660
What's so special about that?

11:57.740 --> 12:00.540
In all the 700 years, nobody's ever done it.

12:00.620 --> 12:02.180
Right, what do you do?

12:19.380 --> 12:21.740
Right, chaps, thank you! Thank you.

12:22.900 --> 12:25.980
Let it be known that HM Abrahams
of Gonville and Caius...

12:26.060 --> 12:29.060
has formally made challenge
for the college dash.

12:30.540 --> 12:32.260
You show 'em, Harold!

12:32.340 --> 12:34.700
For those not familiar with the rules...

12:34.780 --> 12:38.500
The challenger will attempt
to run around the court perimeter...

12:38.580 --> 12:40.860
to and from a point beneath the clock...

12:40.940 --> 12:43.980
within the time taken
by the clock to strike midday.

12:44.060 --> 12:47.940
A distance traditionally
recognised as one of 188 paces.

12:48.020 --> 12:51.460
I say, Abrahams, what have you got
on your feet? Rockets?

12:51.540 --> 12:53.940
The challenge will commence on the...

12:54.020 --> 12:57.740
- Abrahams, you haven't got a chance!
- Do it for Israel!

12:57.820 --> 13:00.220
The challenge commences
on the stroke of one.

13:00.300 --> 13:03.300
The challenger must finish
before the stroke of 12.

13:03.380 --> 13:05.460
Come on, Abrahams, you swank!

13:05.580 --> 13:08.020
Will the challenger make himself ready?

13:15.780 --> 13:18.780
This Abrahams.
What do you know about him?

13:18.860 --> 13:20.860
Repton chap.

13:20.940 --> 13:22.260
Jewish.

13:22.340 --> 13:25.700
- His father's a financier in the city.
- Financier?

13:25.780 --> 13:28.340
What's that supposed to mean, I wonder?

13:28.420 --> 13:30.500
I imagine he lends money.

13:31.220 --> 13:33.300
Exactly.

13:33.380 --> 13:35.620
And what do they say about the son?

13:35.700 --> 13:38.660
Academically sound. Arrogant.

13:38.740 --> 13:40.740
Defensive to the point of pugnacity.

13:40.860 --> 13:43.420
Mm. As they invariably are.

13:44.060 --> 13:47.020
Yet possessing
a keen sense of duty and loyalty.

13:50.500 --> 13:53.020
Do they say he can run?

13:53.100 --> 13:54.940
Like the wind.

13:59.020 --> 14:02.660
Gentlemen, would you draw back, please?
Away from the course.

14:02.740 --> 14:04.420
Thank you.

14:04.500 --> 14:06.580
Mr Abrahams, your position, please.

14:07.380 --> 14:10.020
Owing to the absence
of any other challenger...

14:10.140 --> 14:12.020
Mr Abrahams will run alone.

14:12.100 --> 14:14.220
Not so, Mr Starter!

14:17.980 --> 14:20.300
Your name and college, if you please, sir.

14:20.380 --> 14:23.300
Lindsay. I race beside my friend here.

14:23.380 --> 14:27.060
We challenge in the name
of Repton, Eton and Caius.

14:30.300 --> 14:32.780
<i>- I didn't know you ran.</i>
- Nor I you.

14:32.860 --> 14:36.620
Some chap just told me about this.
I thought I'd come and push you along.

14:36.740 --> 14:38.260
- Delighted.
- Splendid.

14:38.340 --> 14:39.460
Good luck.

14:39.540 --> 14:42.460
Gentlemen, to your marks, if you please.

14:44.620 --> 14:47.500
Now remember, on the first strike of 12.

15:12.660 --> 15:14.740
Come on!

15:33.260 --> 15:35.140
<i>Eight!</i>

15:36.300 --> 15:38.380
Nine!

15:39.900 --> 15:41.980
Ten!

15:42.940 --> 15:44.540
- <i>Eleven!</i>
- Go on! Go on!

16:01.140 --> 16:03.020
Did they both do it?

16:03.100 --> 16:05.180
I think not.

16:05.260 --> 16:08.700
- Young Lindsay failed by a whisker.
- Pity.

16:08.780 --> 16:12.900
<i>Well, it's been done.</i>
<i>And by a Caius man! You must be very proud.</i>

16:12.980 --> 16:15.060
<i>The first man in seven centuries.</i>

16:15.140 --> 16:20.340
<i>Perhaps they really are</i>
<i>God's chosen people, after all.</i>

16:22.060 --> 16:24.740
<i>I doubt if there's a swifter man</i>
<i>in the kingdom.</i>

16:27.220 --> 16:29.300
Get to your marks.

16:33.620 --> 16:35.900
Get set.

17:12.940 --> 17:17.140
<i>He may be your best friend, Sandy,</i>
<i>but he's my best brother.</i>

17:17.220 --> 17:20.540
<i>I'm thinking of him</i>
<i>and not your blessed athletics team.</i>

17:20.619 --> 17:23.660
<i>His heart's set on following Father</i>
<i>in the mission.</i>

17:23.740 --> 17:26.859
Do you not think he's busy enough
without taking up racing?

17:26.940 --> 17:30.100
He's fast, Jennie.
You've seen him with a ball in his hands.

17:30.180 --> 17:32.340
I've seen him with a Bible in his hands.

17:32.420 --> 17:34.500
And I know which is the most important.

17:34.580 --> 17:36.660
You can't deny him the chance.

17:36.740 --> 17:39.420
Get him on the track, I'm telling you...

17:39.500 --> 17:42.220
Don't tell me, Sandy. I don't want to hear.

17:42.300 --> 17:44.340
Eric's special to me. Precious.

17:44.420 --> 17:48.180
I don't want his work spoilt
with all this running talk, do you hear?

17:57.020 --> 18:00.140
There you are. Well done.

18:08.180 --> 18:10.340
You know, ladies and gentlemen...

18:10.460 --> 18:14.100
one of the compensations
of achieving a certain notoriety...

18:14.180 --> 18:15.900
if only as a rugby player...

18:15.980 --> 18:19.140
is that occasionally
you're asked to give things away.

18:21.100 --> 18:23.620
It's often said that giving beats receiving.

18:23.700 --> 18:25.620
Let me tell you...

18:25.700 --> 18:28.420
the look of delight
on those little boys' faces...

18:28.500 --> 18:33.020
was worth ten of the tin pots gathering
dust on my Edinburgh sideboard.

18:34.780 --> 18:37.100
When we were in China, my father here...

18:37.180 --> 18:41.140
was always waxing lyrical
about his wee home in the glen.

18:41.980 --> 18:44.420
But being oriental-born myself...

18:44.500 --> 18:47.180
like my brothers and my sister here...

18:47.260 --> 18:49.980
I suffered from a natural incredulity.

18:51.100 --> 18:53.180
But looking about me now...

18:53.260 --> 18:55.340
the heather on the hills...

18:56.660 --> 18:58.980
I can see he was right.

18:59.060 --> 19:01.140
It's very special.

19:05.500 --> 19:07.500
Thank you for welcoming us home.

19:07.580 --> 19:09.100
And thank you...

19:09.180 --> 19:12.620
for reminding me that I am,
and will be whilst I breathe...

19:14.540 --> 19:16.900
a Scot.

19:20.780 --> 19:23.060
Mr Provost, sir.

19:23.140 --> 19:25.980
Before you allow Eric here to go...

19:26.380 --> 19:30.420
Is it not true that the main event
of the meeting is still to be run?

19:30.500 --> 19:32.220
<i>It is. Aye.</i>

19:32.300 --> 19:34.500
The 200-yards open championship.

19:34.580 --> 19:38.140
It's the last event
of this gathering, by tradition.

19:38.220 --> 19:41.540
Do you not think,
if we can find him some kit...

19:41.660 --> 19:45.580
we might persuade Scotland's
finest wing to show us his paces?

19:48.700 --> 19:50.780
What do you say, Eric?

20:01.220 --> 20:03.540
<i>To your marks!</i>

20:03.620 --> 20:04.980
Get set!

21:15.300 --> 21:17.820
Didn't I tell you, Eric? Didn't I tell you?

21:22.900 --> 21:25.900
Surely a touch of liberality
would do no harm.

21:25.980 --> 21:29.500
Sandy, the kingdom of God
is not a democracy.

21:29.580 --> 21:32.140
The Lord never seeks re-election.

21:32.220 --> 21:34.900
There's no discussion, no deliberation...

21:34.980 --> 21:37.540
no referenda as to which road to take.

21:38.380 --> 21:40.580
There's one right, one wrong...

21:40.660 --> 21:42.740
one absolute ruler.

21:42.820 --> 21:47.460
- A dictator, you mean.
- Aye, but a benign, loving dictator.

21:47.540 --> 21:50.180
So much for your freedom of choice.

21:50.260 --> 21:52.420
<i>You've still got a choice, Sandy.</i>

21:53.340 --> 21:55.580
Nobody's forcing you to follow it.

22:00.420 --> 22:02.700
Hey, hey!

22:03.900 --> 22:06.060
- Do you know what day it is?
- Yeah.

22:06.140 --> 22:08.220
- Tell me, then.
- Sunday.

22:08.300 --> 22:10.940
The Sabbath's not a day
for playing football, is it?

22:11.020 --> 22:12.580
No.

22:12.660 --> 22:15.940
- Are you up early in the morning?
- Me ma gets me up at seven.

22:16.020 --> 22:18.100
We'll have a game then, then. OK?

22:18.180 --> 22:20.260
Mr Liddell, is it OK if me da comes?

22:20.340 --> 22:22.580
Sure. Bring your whole family.

22:22.660 --> 22:24.740
I'll give ye a five-goal start.

22:24.820 --> 22:27.180
You've got a train to catch at nine.

22:27.300 --> 22:29.380
There's plenty of time.

22:29.460 --> 22:32.940
Do you want the kid to grow up
thinking God's a spoilsport?

22:36.740 --> 22:39.380
If I may, I'd like to propose a toast.

22:39.460 --> 22:41.180
To the Liddell family...

22:41.260 --> 22:43.820
whom I'm fortunate enough
to call my friends.

22:43.900 --> 22:46.780
The Reverend JD, Mrs L, young Ernest.

22:47.660 --> 22:50.740
<i>Bon voyage and safe journey back to China.</i>

22:50.860 --> 22:53.220
May the years ahead be happy and content.

22:53.300 --> 22:56.700
For those who remain,
may God protect them...

22:56.780 --> 22:58.500
inspire them...

22:58.580 --> 23:00.420
and lead them to glory.

23:00.500 --> 23:02.700
Thank you, Sandy. That was very nice.

23:02.780 --> 23:05.580
I'm relying on you now
to keep them all out of mischief.

23:05.660 --> 23:10.060
That I will, Mrs L. If they do transgress,
I'll pop the details on a postcard.

23:10.140 --> 23:13.220
You can read all about it
before you can say Marco Polo.

23:13.300 --> 23:15.460
Cost you a fortune in postage stamps.

23:15.540 --> 23:17.900
Don't worry. I shall protect my investment.

23:17.980 --> 23:21.060
I'm going to rule you with a rod of iron.

23:22.740 --> 23:25.140
We're going to have to watch ourselves!

23:28.820 --> 23:31.020
You're a very lucky young man, Eric.

23:31.100 --> 23:33.380
You're the proud possessor of many gifts.

23:33.460 --> 23:36.380
And it's your sacred duty
to put them to good use.

23:36.460 --> 23:39.980
Dad's right. Run like we know you can,
strong and true.

23:40.060 --> 23:42.940
The mission cannot but gain
by your success.

23:43.980 --> 23:46.580
What we need now is a muscular Christian.

23:47.100 --> 23:49.980
To make folks sit up and notice.

23:50.060 --> 23:52.500
How good are you, Eric?

23:53.260 --> 23:56.820
Sandy reckons he'll run for Scotland
before the month's out.

23:56.900 --> 23:59.460
Then after that... the sky's the limit.

23:59.540 --> 24:01.020
Meaning what?

24:02.020 --> 24:04.100
The Olympic Games, maybe?

24:05.860 --> 24:09.340
Eric, you can praise the Lord
by peeling a spud...

24:09.420 --> 24:11.500
if you peel it to perfection.

24:11.580 --> 24:14.860
Don't compromise.
Compromise is a language of the devil.

24:14.940 --> 24:16.980
Run in God's name...

24:17.100 --> 24:19.700
<i>and let the world stand back in wonder.</i>

24:32.300 --> 24:38.220
♪ Lean and his mercy will provide

24:38.300 --> 24:43.980
♪ Trust and thy trusting soul shall prove

24:44.460 --> 24:50.260
♪ Christ is its life and Christ its love

24:56.900 --> 24:59.500
♪ <i>Run the straight race</i>

24:59.580 --> 25:02.820
♪ <i>Through God's good grace</i>

25:03.300 --> 25:05.460
♪ <i>Lift up thine eyes</i>

25:05.540 --> 25:09.180
♪ <i>And seek his face</i>

25:09.260 --> 25:15.540
♪ <i>Life with its way before us lies</i>

25:23.840 --> 25:25.880
You came to see a race today.

25:25.960 --> 25:28.040
To see someone win.

25:28.480 --> 25:30.560
It happened to be me.

25:31.320 --> 25:34.280
But I want you to do more
than just watch a race.

25:35.080 --> 25:37.160
I want you to take part in it.

25:38.280 --> 25:42.040
I want to compare faith to running in a race.

25:43.440 --> 25:45.520
It's hard.

25:45.600 --> 25:47.960
It requires concentration of will.

25:48.520 --> 25:50.600
Energy of soul.

25:52.400 --> 25:54.360
You experience elation...

25:54.440 --> 25:56.520
when the winner breaks the tape...

25:57.480 --> 25:59.840
especially if you've got a bet on it.

26:00.680 --> 26:02.760
But how long does that last?

26:03.360 --> 26:05.920
You go home. Maybe your dinner's burnt.

26:07.040 --> 26:09.480
Maybe you haven't got a job.

26:10.720 --> 26:12.800
So who am I to say believe...

26:13.280 --> 26:16.240
have faith, in the face of life's realities?

26:18.040 --> 26:21.120
I would like to give you
something more permanent...

26:21.200 --> 26:23.280
but I can only point the way.

26:23.840 --> 26:26.360
I have no formula for winning the race.

26:26.800 --> 26:28.880
Everyone runs in her own way...

26:29.000 --> 26:31.080
or his own way.

26:31.160 --> 26:35.120
And where does the power come from
to see the race to its end?

26:37.120 --> 26:39.200
From within.

26:39.960 --> 26:42.040
Jesus said...

26:42.120 --> 26:45.800
"Behold, the kingdom of God is within you."

26:48.160 --> 26:51.840
"If with all your hearts ye truly seek me...

26:51.920 --> 26:54.160
ye shall ever surely find me."

26:54.680 --> 26:56.960
If you commit yourself...

26:57.040 --> 26:59.120
to the love of Christ...

27:00.200 --> 27:03.440
then <i>that is how you run a straight race.</i>

27:10.800 --> 27:13.120
Cheers. Thanks for coming.

27:26.240 --> 27:28.320
It's an ache.

27:29.640 --> 27:31.760
A helplessness.

27:33.600 --> 27:35.720
And an anger.

27:39.680 --> 27:41.760
One feels humiliated.

27:47.520 --> 27:51.720
Sometimes I say to myself,
"Steady on, you're imagining all this."

27:52.520 --> 27:54.600
Then I catch that look again.

27:55.560 --> 27:57.640
Catch it on the edge of a remark.

27:58.480 --> 28:00.960
Feel a cold reluctance in a handshake.

28:07.280 --> 28:09.360
That's my father.

28:09.440 --> 28:11.520
A Lithuanian Jew.

28:12.040 --> 28:14.120
He <i>is alien.</i>

28:14.200 --> 28:17.280
- He's as foreign as a frankfurter.
- A kosher one at that!

28:23.440 --> 28:25.520
I love and admire him.

28:26.880 --> 28:28.960
He worships this country.

28:29.040 --> 28:31.320
From nothing, he built what he believed...

28:31.400 --> 28:34.040
was enough to make
true Englishmen of his sons.

28:35.040 --> 28:37.120
My brother's a doctor.

28:41.640 --> 28:43.720
A leader in his field.

28:44.640 --> 28:48.520
- Which one is he?
- That's me with the curls, on his back.

28:53.240 --> 28:55.320
He wanted for nothing.

28:57.680 --> 28:59.680
And here am I.

28:59.760 --> 29:03.200
<i>Setting up shop</i>
<i>in the finest university in the land.</i>

29:19.080 --> 29:21.160
But the old man forgot one thing.

29:21.960 --> 29:24.040
This England of his is Christian...

29:24.120 --> 29:26.200
and Anglo-Saxon.

29:26.760 --> 29:28.920
And so are her corridors of power.

29:30.520 --> 29:34.400
And those who stalk them
guard them with jealousy and venom.

29:35.440 --> 29:38.800
You're right to study law.
You're quite an advocate.

29:38.880 --> 29:42.480
A rare ethnic advantage.
It's called the gift of the gab.

29:49.280 --> 29:51.960
So what now? Grin and bear it?

29:52.040 --> 29:54.040
No, Aubrey.

29:54.120 --> 29:56.880
I'm going to take them on. All of them.

29:57.440 --> 29:59.520
One by one.

29:59.920 --> 30:02.000
And run them off their feet.

30:06.520 --> 30:12.080
♪ <i>He is an Englishman!</i>

30:12.440 --> 30:18.160
♪ <i>He is an Englishman</i>

30:18.680 --> 30:24.160
♪ <i>For he himself has said it</i>

30:24.280 --> 30:28.480
♪ <i>And it's greatly to his credit</i>

30:28.800 --> 30:32.920
♪ <i>That he is an Englishman</i>

30:39.320 --> 30:41.920
<i>England beckons for sprint blue.</i>

30:42.000 --> 30:44.200
<i>From a special correspondent.</i>

30:47.080 --> 30:50.440
<i>Clean sweep for Cambridge star.</i>

30:51.200 --> 30:53.200
<i>Abrahams hat trick.</i>

30:53.280 --> 30:55.360
<i>From a special correspondent.</i>

31:06.560 --> 31:11.480
♪ <i>But in spite of all temptations</i>

31:11.640 --> 31:15.920
♪ <i>To belong to other nations</i>

31:16.160 --> 31:20.400
♪ <i>He remains an Englishman</i>

31:20.520 --> 31:22.640
♪ <i>He remains an</i>

31:22.720 --> 31:28.640
♪ <i>Englishman</i>

31:28.720 --> 31:33.560
♪ <i>For in spite of all temptations</i>

31:34.000 --> 31:37.600
♪ <i>To belong to other nations</i>

31:38.600 --> 31:42.560
♪ <i>He remains an Englishman</i>

31:42.640 --> 31:45.400
♪ He remains an

31:45.480 --> 31:47.480
♪ Englishman

31:55.600 --> 31:57.560
Bravo!

32:00.080 --> 32:02.360
Bravo, Harold!

